{{Infobox scientist | name = Blaire Van Valkenburgh | birth_date = 1952<ref name="BVVDissertation" /> | birth_place = Washington, D.C.<ref name="VanValkenburghCV" /> | citizenship = [[United States]] | fields = [[Vertebrate Paleontology]], [[Paleobiology]], [[Paleoecology]] | workplaces = University of California Los Angeles (1986-Present) | education = Ph.D. | alma_mater = {{unbulleted list| |[[Stockton State College]]<ref name="VanValkenburghCV" /> |[[Johns Hopkins University]]<ref name="VanValkenburghCV" />}} | thesis_year = 1984<ref name="VanValkenburghCV" /> | doctoral_advisor = [[Robert Bakker]]<ref name="VanValkenburghCV" /> | known_for = quantitative analysis of ecological guild structure in fossil carnivores | awards = {{unbulleted list| | President, [[Society of Vertebrate Paleontology]] <small>2008-2010</small> | Joseph T. Gregory Award, [[Society of Vertebrate Paleontology]] <small>2018</small><ref>http://vertpaleo.org/Annual-Meeting/Annual-Meeting-Home/SVP-2018-program-book-V4-FINAL-with-covers-9-24-18.aspx</ref>}} | website = http://www.eeb.ucla.edu/indivfaculty.php?FacultyKey=1620 }} '''Blaire Van Valkenburgh''' is an American [[paleontologist]] and holds the Donald R. Dickey Chair in Vertebrate Biology in the Department of Ecology and Evolutionary Biology at [[University of California Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Van Valkenburgh, Blaire |url=https://www.eeb.ucla.edu/indivfaculty.php?FacultyKey=1620 |publisher=UCLA |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref><ref name="BVVCenterCollege">{{cite web |last1=Hoffman |first1=Haley |title=Blaire Van Valkenburgh to deliver lecture as part of Phi Beta Kappa's Visiting Scholars program |url=https://www.centre.edu/blaire-van-valkenburg-deliver-lecture-part-phi-beta-kappas-visiting-scholars-program/ |publisher=Center College, Danville, Kentucky |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref> She has served as chair of the department and as associate dean of academic programs in the life sciences at UCLA.
The focus of her research is the [[paleobiology]] and [[paleoecology]] of [[Carnivora]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bates-Duke |first1=Karl |title=Math proves ancient cats could hunt mammoths |url=https://www.futurity.org/math-hypercarnivores-pleistocene-1036332/ |website=Futurity |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref><ref name="BVVTrowelBlazers">{{cite web |title=Blaire Van Valkenburgh: Staring down the saber-tooths |url=https://trowelblazers.com/blaire-van-valkenburgh/ |website=TrowelBlazers |publisher=TrowelBlazers |accessdate=23 Jul 2018}}</ref> Her contributions include quantification of guild structure in fossil carnivore communities and the study of iterative evolution in carnivore feeding adaptations.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Van Valkenburgh |first1=Blaire |title=The impact of large terrestrial carnivores on Pleistocene ecosystems |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |date=2016 |volume=113 |issue=4 |pages=862–867 |doi=10.1073/pnas.1502554112 |pmid=26504224 |pmc=4743832 |url=http://www.pnas.org/content/113/4/862.short}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Van Valkenburgh |first1=Blaire |title=Déjà vu: the evolution of feeding morphologies in the Carnivora |journal=Integrative and Comparative Biology |date=2007 |volume=47 |issue=1 |pages=147–163 |doi=10.1093/icb/icm016 |pmid=21672827 |url=https://www.futurity.org/math-hypercarnivores-pleistocene-1036332/}}</ref>
Van Valkenburgh received a bachelors degree from Stockton State College in New Jersey in 1974,<ref name="BVVDissertation" /> a Ph.D. in Vertebrate Paleobiology from [[Johns Hopkins University]] in 1984, where she worked with [[Robert Bakker]],<ref name="BVVDissertation">{{cite book |last1=Van Valkenburgh |first1=Blaire |title=A Morphological Analysis of Ecological Separation Within Past And Present Predator Guilds (Carnivore, Competition) |date=1984 |publisher=PhD Dissertation, Johns Hopkins University |location=Baltimore Maryland |pages=1–286 |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/303319590 |accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref> after which she worked as a postdoctoral fellow with [[Alan Walker (anthropologist)|Alan Walker]] at Johns Hopkins<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walker |first1=Alan |last2=Shipman |first2=Pat |title=The Ape in the Tree: an Intellectual and Natural History of Proconsul |date=2005 |publisher=Belknap Press of Harvard University |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |isbn=978-0-674-01675-0 |pages=1–291 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DauBuaRsJl0C}}</ref> before moving to UCLA in 1986.<ref name="VanValkenburghCV">{{cite web |last1=Van Valkenburgh |first1=Blaire |title=Curriculum Vitae |url=https://www.eeb.ucla.edu/Faculty/VanValkenburgh/BVV_CV_2018_Prof7.pdf |publisher=UCLA |accessdate=22 Jul 2018}}</ref> Van Valkenburgh served as president of the [[Society of Vertebrate Paleontology]] from 2008 to 2010<ref>{{cite web |title=Society of Vertebrate Paleontology Past Presidents |url=http://vertpaleo.org/the-Society/Leadership/SVP_Past_Presidents.aspx |publisher=Society of Vertebrate Paleontology |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> and as associate editor of the [[Journal of Vertebrate Paleontology]] from 2011 to 2017.<ref name="VanValkenburghCV" />
