{{Starbox short | name = ChaHα8 | constell = [[Chamaeleon (constellation)|Chamaeleon]] | ra = {{RA|11|07|46.102}}<ref name=SIMBAD>{{cite simbad| title = CHSM 10837| accessdate = 29 November 2016 }}</ref> | dec = {{DEC|-77|40|08.94}}<ref name=SIMBAD/> | dist_ly = 522 | dist_pc = 160<ref name=Joergens2007/> | class = M5.75–M6.5<ref name=Joergens2007/> | appmag_v = 20.1<ref name=SIMBAD/> | names = [[2MASS]] J11074610-7740089<ref name=SIMBAD/> | Simbad = CHSM+10837 }} '''ChaHα8''' (also written ChaHa8 when [[Greek alphabet|Greek letters]] are unavailable) is a [[brown dwarf]] 522 light years from Earth discovered in 2000.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Comerón|first1=F.|last2=Neuhäuser|first2=R.|last3=Kaas|first3=A. A.|title=Probing the brown dwarf population of the Chamaeleon I star forming region|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|date=2000|volume=359|pages=269–288|bibcode = 2000A&A...359..269C }}</ref> It was found in 2007 to have a low-mass substellar companion in orbit around it.<ref name=Joergens2007>{{cite journal| year=2007| title=16–20 Jupiter mass RV companion orbiting the brown dwarf candidate ChaHa8| first=V.| last= Joergens|author2=A. Mueller| arxiv=0707.3744|bibcode = 2007ApJ...666L.113J |doi = 10.1086/521825 }}</ref> The companion has a mass of 25–31 [[Jupiter mass]]es and orbits with a period of 5.2 years and an eccentricity of 0.59.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Joergens|first1=V.|last2=Müller|first2=A.|last3=Reffert|first3=S.|title=Improved radial velocity orbit of the young binary brown dwarf candidate Cha Hα 8|journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|date=2010|volume=521|issue=A24|doi=10.1051/0004-6361/201014853|arxiv = 1006.2383 |bibcode = 2010A&A...521A..24J }}</ref>
